0254 C4.37533831,22.9351963 4.35092131,22.7683321 4.4017231,22.616585 L7.00408269,14.8432273 L0.212864685,10.0456121 C-0.0140805533,9.88528803 -0.0680876559,9.57134421 0.0922364448,9.34439897 C0.186520784,9.21093568 0.339749724,9.1315756 0.503157148,9.1315756 L8.910885,9.1315756 L11.5230185,1.34326985 C11.6113744,1.0798288 11.8965622,0.937894292 12.1600033,1.02625024 C12.3095218,1.07639751 12.4268756,1.19375135 12.4770229,1.34326985 Z"></path></g></svg></span><span class="RatingStar RatingStar--small"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" role="presentation"><g stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"><path class="RatingStar__backgroundFill" d="M12.4770229,1.34326985 L15.0891563,9.1315756 L23.4968842,9.1315756 C23.7747474,9.1315756 24,9.35682823 24,9.63469143 C24,9.79809886 23.9206399,9.95132779 23.7871766,10.0456121 L16.9959586,14.8432273 L19.5982827,22.6117477 C19.6865419,22.8752212 19.5445026,23.1603569 19.2810291,23.2486161 C19.1293386,23.2994298 18.9625235,23.2750752 18.8316924,23.1830139 L12.0000207,18.3758025 L5.1685337,23.1876292 C4.94136559,23.3476374 4.62749722,23.2931935 4.46748907,23.0660254 C4.37533831,22.9351963 4.35092131,22.7683321 4.4017231,22.616585 L7.00408269,14.8432273 L0.212864685,10.0456121 C-0.0140805533,9.88528803 -0.0680876559,9.57134421 0.0922364448,9.34439897 C0.186520784,9.21093568 0.339749724,9.1315756 0.503157148,9.1315756 L8.910885,9.1315756 L11.5230185,1.34326985 C11.6113744,1.0798288 11.8965622,0.937894292 12.1600033,1.02625024 C12.3095218,1.07639751 12.4268756,1.19375135 12.4770229,1.34326985 Z"></path></g></svg></span></span></div><span class="Text Text__body3"><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1372296601">Edited <!-- -->February 16, 2019</a></span></section><section class="ReviewText"><section class="ReviewText__content"><div class="TruncatedText"><div class="TruncatedText__text TruncatedText__text--5" data-testid="contentContainer"><div><span class="Formatted">Well Done. This historical novel is written by a lawyer who understands the laws governing slavery, their intrepretations, courtroom dynamics.<br /><br />Only once early in the book is there an outright lecture on slavery laws. Just that one time. <br /><br />Because the character and person Dred Scott are placed an a historical setting, the writer Mark L Shurtleff oeriodical keeps the reader informed of (Justice) Roger B Taney and (President) Abraham Lincoln: Where they were and what they were doing. Shurtleff explains Tamey's decision, but never justifies. (I think Shurtleff is a bit mystified too). Shurtleff also explains how Lincoln was elected president as a near-direct result of the Dred Scott Case. <br /><br />Glad I read this. The explanation of why Taney gave his fateful and disrespectful opinion at least gave reason--none of other. I am glad to see that upon entering office Lincoln was taking action to free the slaves--in whatever limited ways. He was working from Intention. There can be no better way to work--however horrifying and frustrating the time lapse was to the black folk of the day.<br /><br />Well Done. Enjoyed the information and read.</span></div></div></div></section></section><section class="ReviewCard__tags"><ul class="CollapsableList"><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/list/24011982?shelf=african-american" class="Button Button--tag-inline Button--small"><span class="Button__labelItem">african-american</span></a> <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/list/24011982?shelf=civil-rights" class="Button Button--tag-inline Button--small"><span class="Button__labelItem">civil-rights</span></a> <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/list/24011982?shelf=grassroots-movements" class="Button Button--tag-inline Button--small"><span class="Button__labelItem">grassroots-movements</span></a> <div class="Button__container"><button type="button" class="Button Button--tag-inline Button--small" aria-label="Show all items in the list"><span class="Button__labelItem">...more</span></button></div